ndian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Crespy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jaime, Juan, Mercedes, Racquel, Alberto, Alejandro, Consuelo, Eduardo, Jose, Jose Manuel, Migdalia, Pedro.  Jewish Aron, Nissim.","Catalan (<b>Crespí</b>): from a personal name, the Catalan equivalent of   Crispin  .","Italian (northern): variant of   Crespo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Crispin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."]}]},{"name":"Thibault","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Germanic.  See  <b>Theobald</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thibault de Crespy was born in France. He married Elizabeth de London before 1048, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1141."},"et":{"–1141":"–1141","–Female":"Surnud","1048–1143":"1048–1143","before 1048":"enne 1048","1048":"1048","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","about 1048":"umbes 1048","Crepi, France":"Prantsusmaa","Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–1141":"–1141","–Female":"Kuollut","1048–1143":"1048–1143","before 1048":"ennen vuotta 1048","1048":"1048","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","about 1048":"noin 1048","Crepi, France":"Ranska","Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"–1141":"–1141","–Female":"Décédée","1048–1143":"1048–1143","before 1048":"avant 1048","1048":"1048","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","about 1048":"environ 1048","Crepi, France":"France","Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Thibault de Crespy est né à France. Il a épousé Elizabeth de London avant 1048, à France. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1141."},"de":{"–1141":"–1141","–Female":"Verstorben","1048–1143":"1048–1143","before 1048":"vor 1048","1048":"1048","1143":"1143","1141":"1141","about 1048":"um 1048","Crepi, France":"Frankreich","Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, France":"Bagneux, Hauts-de-Seine, Île-de-France, Frankreich","France":"Frankreich","lifeSummary":"Thibault de Crespy wurde in Frankreic